every B2B founder/CEO right now is one product update away from becoming a feature of ChatGPT or Claude Code... 

another way to say is that the biggest threat to your retention isn't your competitor.

it's a $20/month tool that does 80% of what you do.

that's not hyperbole. 

one CEO in my roundtable said something that paused the conversation and everyone nodded:

"customers are quietly canceling not because they found something better, but because they found something good enough." 

and that distinction matters more than most CEOs of big and small companies realize.

we've spent years building retention playbooks around competition. 
better onboarding. 
stronger CS teams. 
more executive relationships. 

all of it was designed for a world where the threat had a name, a sales team, and a demo.

AI doesn't have any of that. 

it just works. quietly. until your renewal conversation.

the uncomfortable question every B2B leader needs to sit with: 

is your product 10x better than the AI version of your product? 
not feature-for-feature. 
but in outcomes. in time saved. in confidence delivered.

if the answer is "yes, clearly" — you're fine. 

if the answer is "we're working on it" or "our customers wouldn't switch" — that's the number one thing to fix before you touch your gtm strategy.

the GTM OS has a customer success pillar for a reason. 

but the whole framework assumes you're fighting for someone's business. 

you also have to now fight for their belief that software is still the right answer.

that's a different conversation. and most of us are not ready for it.

am i wrong?
